Class KBTermImpl

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cyc.kb.client.KBObjectImpl

    Direct Known Subclasses:
    KBCollectionImpl, KBIndividualImpl

    public class KBTermImpl
extends KBObjectImpl
implements KBTerm
    A KBTerm is a facade for any #$CycLDenotationalTerm, but in the API its purpose is to create terms that are only known to be #$Thing.

      • findOrCreate

        public static KBTerm findOrCreate(String nameOrId,
                  KBCollection constraintCol)
                           throws CreateException,
                                  KBTypeException
        Find or create a KBTerm object named nameOrId, and also make it an instance of constraintCol in the default context specified by KBAPIDefaultContext.forAssertion(). If no object exists in the KB with the name nameOrId, one will be created, and it will be asserted to be an instance of constraintCol. If there is already an object in the KB called nameOrId, and it is already a constraintCol, it will be returned. If it is not already a constraintCol, but can be made so by addition of assertions to the KB, such assertions will be made, and the object will be returned. If the object in the KB cannot be turned into a constraintCol by adding assertions, a KBTypeConflictExceptionwill be thrown.
        Parameters:
        nameOrId - the string representation or the HLID of the term
        constraintCol - the collection that this term will instantiate
        Returns:
        a new KBTerm
        Throws:
        KBTypeException
        CreateException

      • isValidCore

        protected boolean isValidCore(CycObject cycObject)
                       throws KBApiRuntimeException,
                              KBApiServerSideException
        This not part of the public, supported KB API. Check that the candidate core object is valid for this type. This is part of the bootstrapping process, where we check the core before we build a KB Object. At this point, we can not use any KB API methods or KBObjectImpl.getCore(). This checks the validity of only KBTerm subclasses. The core validity for Assertion and its subclasses, Sentence, Variable and Symbol are handled by the individual classes If a Variable is wrapped by any subclass of KBTerm, then it is always considered valid core. This is to allow representing a #$CycLDenotationalTerm and #$CycLVariable of a given type (#$Collection) using same KBTerm subclass.
        Parameters:
        cycObject - the object that is checked for type given by getTypeString()
        Returns:
        if a cycObject is of a given type
        Throws:
        KBApiRuntimeException - if there is a problem connecting to Cyc
        KBApiServerSideException - if there is problem executing a SubL command NOTE: This does not throw KBTypeException just because there is a server error.
